Parses `ctx-cage`'s argv into a `Mode` the lifecycle executes; owns mode resolution and the spend gate, but not path resolution (done by host binaries) or actual sandboxing.

Mode precedence is strict: `--self-test <kind>` wins outright and conflicts with any `--task`/`--task-file`/`--interactive`; `--task` and `--task-file` are mutually exclusive with each other and with `--interactive`; absent all of those, default is `Mode::Interactive`. All conflict checks happen in `check_flag_conflicts` before `compute_mode` runs, so `compute_mode` can assume a clean, single-mode `Cli`.

Billed modes (`Task`, `Interactive`) are double-gated: `resolve_mode(cli, allow_spend)` rejects them unless `allow_spend` is true, but the caller supplies that bool — it's meant to come from `--allow-spend` OR `CTX_CAGE_ALLOW_SPEND=1`, ORed together by the host binary before calling in; this file doesn't read env vars itself. `mode_is_billed` is the single source of truth for which modes cost money — `SelfTestStub` is always free.

`TaskFlags`/`SpendFlags` are split into `#[command(flatten)]` sub-structs specifically to dodge clippy's `struct_excessive_bools` lint without an `#[allow]`, per workspace policy banning those.

`CONTRACT` is a hard-synced string: the `contracts` battery test fails if this text drifts from the generated tool-contract block in `CLAUDE.md`/`README.md` — edit both together.

`resolve_mode(cli: &Cli, allow_spend: bool) -> Result<Mode, ResolveError>` is the sole public entry point; reads `--task-file` from disk (`ResolveError::Io` on failure) as part of resolution, so it can fail on I/O, not just flag logic.